,"id":"31567"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42980"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92392"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents with a three month history of progressive dyspnoea, reduced exercise tolerance and cough. He has a ten pack-year smoking history and is a retired construction worker. His medical history includes hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia, for which he takes ramipril and atorvastatin. On examination there is decreased lung expansion and bilateral fine inspiratory crepitations at the bases. Pulmonary function tests are conducted.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following results would be consistent with the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["FEV1/FVC 65% predicted, normal FVC, high DLCO","FEV1/FVC 60% predicted, normal FVC, low DLCO","FEV1/FVC 85% predicted, low FVC, normal DLCO","FEV1/FVC 80% predicted, low FVC, low DLCO","FEV1/FVC 85% predicted, normal FVC, normal DLCO"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation is consistent with idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis, with the key physical finding of bibasal fine inspiratory crepitations. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn pulmonary function tests, this would present as a restrictive pattern \u003Cstrong\u003EFEV1/FVC \u0026gt;70% predicted and low FVC, and with a low DLCO\u003C/strong\u003E, suggestive of an abnormality at the alveolar level resulting in a decrease in gas transfer. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOption A \u003Cstrong\u003E(FEV1/FVC 65% predicted, normal FVC, high DLCO)\u003C/strong\u003E is an obstructive picture with an elevated DLCO, which could be consistent with asthma. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOption B \u003Cstrong\u003E(FEV1/FVC 60% predicted, normal FVC, low DLCO) \u003C/strong\u003Eis an obstructive picture, which could suggest chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. While COPD is consistent with the significant smoking history and symptomatic picture, the absence of typical physical examination findings (e.g. barrel-chested, hyper-resonant percussion note) makes this lower on the differential diagnoses. While inspiratory crackles can be found in COPD, they are more likely to be coarse in nature. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOption C \u003Cstrong\u003E(FEV1/FVC 85% predicted, low FVC, normal DLCO) \u003C/strong\u003Eshows a restrictive pattern with normal alveolar gas transfer and is more consistent with extra pulmonary causes of restrictive lung disease, such as chest wall deformities or neuromuscular disorders. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOption E \u003Cstrong\u003E(FEV1/FVC 85% predicted, normal FVC, normal DLCO)\u003C/strong\u003E is a normal pulmonary function test.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Obstructive lung diseases involve airway narrowing or blockage, and includes COPD, asthma, and bronchiectasis.","In restrictive lung diseases such as pulmonary fibrosis and interstitial lung disease, the lung tissue is damaged, preventing adequate lung expansion."],"references":["Langan RC, Goodbred AJ. Office Spirometry: Indications and Interpretation. American family physician. 2020 Mar 15;101(6):362\u20138"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75698"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"193"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75698","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75698"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-17T16:00:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-17T16:00:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"193"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92392"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u